# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: alexandria-virginia
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] The **11th New York Infantry Regiment** was an infantry regiment of the Union Army in the early years of the American Civil War.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] The regiment was organized in New York City in May 1861 as a Zouave regiment, known for its unusual dress and drill style, by Colonel Elmer E.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] Drawn from the ranks of the city's many volunteer fire companies, the unit was known alternately as the Ellsworth Zouaves, First Fire Zouaves, First Regiment New York Zouaves, and U.S.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] The unit was among the first to occupy the territory of a Confederate state when it captured Alexandria, Virginia, on May 24, 1861, less than 24 hours after the Commonwealth seceded from the Union.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] The regiment suffered extensive casualties during the First Battle of Bull Run during the fighting on Henry House Hill and while serving as the rear guard for the retreating Union Army.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] The regiment would later be stationed near Hampton Roads during the Peninsula Campaign, but experienced little fighting.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] Sent back to New York City in May 1862, the regiment was mustered out of service on June 2, 1862.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] There were several attempts to reorganize as a light infantry regiment through the summer of 1863, and many new enlistees were involved in suppressing the New York Draft Riots but those efforts failed and the enlistees were transferred to the 17th New York Veteran Volunteer Infantry Regiment.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] On April 15, 1861, President Lincoln issued an Executive Order calling for 75,000 ninety-day enlistments to "repossess the forts, places, and property which have been seized from the Union." That day, Lincoln wrote Ellsworth asking for his assistance in raising a regiment.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] Ellsworth had known the president well, from having assisted in organizing his campaign for the presidency in 1860 and received a commission to organize the 11th New York Infantry as a 90-day regiment.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] To the enlistees, a common yet often unknown stipulation included 90 days of service to the Federal government and up to two years of service to the state.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] This was not always communicated to the men who enlisted, including those of the 11th New York.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] Ellsworth's military knowledge came from a lifetime of studying military tactics, history, and manuals; and later as colonel of Chicago's National Guard Cadets.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] He never achieved his dream of attending West Point, as he could not gain the needed sponsorship.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] He was introduced to the famous French Zouaves through the teachings of his fencing instructor, Charles DeVillers, a former French Zouave.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] Ellsworth introduced this drill team to the flashy Zouave uniforms and drill that emulated French colonial troops in Algeria and turned the group, renamed the U.S.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] Zouave Cadets, into a national champion drill team.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] A national tour in 1860 brought Ellsworth to the attention of Abraham Lincoln, for whom the unit performed hundreds of military drill movements with their muskets and bayonets.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] When a civil war seemed unavoidable, Ellsworth proceeded to New York City to recruit his own regiment from the city's volunteer fire companies, stating: "I want the New York Firemen, for there are no more effective men in the country, and none with whom I can do so much.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] They are sleeping on a volcano at Washington and I want men who can go into a fight now." Two days after his arrival, Ellsworth awarded officer commissions to several foremen of the volunteer fire companies and began recruiting in earnest.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] Within four days, 2,300 men had answered Ellsworth's call.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] A selection of only the most desirable men cut that number to 1,100, which was considered a regiment's full strength.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] When the state could not afford to supply the new troops, fundraisers were successful in raising $60,000 for the regiment, enough to provide uniforms, several different models of Sharps rifles, and provisions.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] Along the way, they received from the fire department a large white flag measuring 68 inches (1.7 m) by 54 inches (1.4 m) to serve as the regimental colors.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] Charlotte Augusta Gibbes also presented the unit with a flag.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] Unbeknownst to the regiment, Washington D.C. had postponed their departure because they did not comply with army regulations.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] Wool, commander of the Department of the East, knew of the postponement, but allowed the men to embark, unaware the steamer *Baltic* carried no provisions.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] Quartermaster Arthur quickly purchased five-day rations, by paying a higher price, and hired three tug boats to catch the steamer to deliver them.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] The *Baltic* arrived in Annapolis, Maryland where the men boarded a train to Washington, D.C..
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] In Washington, men in the regiment broke into taverns, frightened women, swedged on meals and pursued imagined Confederates.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] They were returned to New York City and quartered in Battery Park.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] Their public antics and insubordination continued.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] Arthur had arrested any Fire Zouave found on the streets and jailed them on a steamer.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] When the number jailed reached 400 the steamer embarked to Hampton Roads where the men were banded with another regiment.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] The regiment arrived in Washington, D.C., on the evening of May 2.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] There, they completed additional training and performed picket duty throughout the district.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] While quartered on the floor of the United States House of Representatives, the enlisted men took it upon themselves to set up a mock session, passing a law first abolishing the House of Representatives, then the Union and reconstituting both in a manner of their liking.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] The more embarrassing and lawbreaking actions by the regiment included the burning of fences, which resulted in a letter of reprimand from Brigadier General Joseph K.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] Mansfield along with six enlisted men being removed and sent back to New York.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] On May 7, the 11th New York was officially sworn into Federal service by Brig.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] Irvin McDowell on the East Front of the unfinished Capitol in the presence of Lincoln, his son Tad and personal secretary John Hay.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] On May 9, the regiment had an opportunity to apply their experience as firefighters when asked to help extinguish a blaze at the Willard Hotel.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] Upon receiving word from General Mansfield, commander of the Department of Washington, Ellsworth dispatched ten men from each company to attend to the fire.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] Soon however, the entire regiment responded to the blaze.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] With Ellsworth having more men on the scene than the Washington Fire Department, he claimed the fire chief's trumpet and assumed command of the incident.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] When the fire was extinguished, Henry Willard, owner of the hotel, invited the regiment to breakfast and money was collected providing them with $500.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] After nine days quartered at the capitol, the men of the 11th New York were moved to the heights near the Insane Asylum to Camp Lincoln.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] This move would allow for easy transport across the Potomac and into Virginia when necessary.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] While just five miles (8 km) from the capitol, the standard of living the men were used to had changed dramatically, as their usual foodstuffs were replaced with beef steak, dry bread, and coffee.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] Ellsworth wrote to his fiancé that they had not had butter in a week.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] When the Commonwealth of Virginia seceded from the Union on May 23, the regiment was ordered to assist in the occupation of Arlington Heights and Alexandria, Virginia, directly across the Potomac River from Washington.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] On May 24, the regiment boarded the steamers *Baltimore* and *Mount Vernon* and was transported across the Potomac, landing at the Alexandria wharves under the guard of the gunboat *Pawnee*.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] The 11th New York was one of eight to enter Virginia, and Ellsworth's men met no resistance as they moved through the streets.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] After landing, members of Company E under Captain Leveridge were sent to take the railroad station, while Ellsworth, Major Charles Loeser, Lieutenant H.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] Winser and several men from Company A set out to secure the telegraph office.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] On the way there, Ellsworth spotted a Confederate flag atop the Marshall House inn.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] It was the same flag Ellsworth had seen for weeks from the White House during his visits with Lincoln.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] Ellsworth's group entered the inn and quickly cut down the flag, but they encountered the proprietor, James Jackson, as they descended the stairs.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] Jackson killed Ellsworth with a shotgun blast to the chest, and Cpl.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] Francis Brownell responded in kind by fatally shooting the innkeeper.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] Farnham, the regiment's lieutenant colonel, was the obvious choice to take command.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] He was reluctant, however, labeling it an "unwelcome responsibility".
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] His appointment was graded as temporary, he was not commissioned as the regiment's colonel and remained at rank while in its command.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] Regardless, he was a popular choice both with the enlisted men and in New York.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] The regiment remained on guard duty in and around Alexandria until July 15, 1861, when orders were received attaching the regiment to Orlando B.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] Irvin McDowell's Army of Northeast Virginia.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] They were to march out the next morning.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] From July 16 to 21, the regiment advanced to intercept Brig.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] Beauregard's Confederate Army of the Potomac.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] Three of McDowell's five divisions advanced towards Bull Run, outside the railroad junction at Manassas, Virginia.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] The 11th New York expected to first engage Confederates at Fairfax Court House on July 17, only to find that they had pulled back towards Centreville, leaving Quaker Guns in their place.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] These movements were to precipitate the first large-scale battle of the Civil War.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] The Zouaves' first major combat experience occurred during the First Battle of Bull Run.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] On the morning of July 21, Farnham's men were awoken at 2:00 a.m. to begin their march to intercept the Confederate army.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] McDowell's plan for the day was for divisions under Colonel Daniel Tyler and Brig.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] Heintzelman to cross Bull Run at Sudley Ford, expected to be only several miles north of their camp.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] Poor scouting by Union chief engineer John G.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] Barnard resulted in a 14-mile (23 km) march for men entering battle that morning.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] During the march, lead units engaged skirmishers east of Sudley's Ford with artillery in the early dawn.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] McDowell had divided his three divisions, sending Heintzelman to the north, sweeping down to cover the Union right, and thus his was the last division to engage.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] The other two divisions, under Tyler and David Hunter, engaged first on the Union left and center, at Matthews Hill.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] With those divisions facing heavy resistance, Heintzelman's division with the 11th New York was called forward at the double-quick.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] One observer commented that the 11th New York looked more like firemen randomly running to a fire than soldiers marching towards the front.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] As the fight moved from Matthews Hill to Henry House Hill, the 11th New York fought beside the 1st Minnesota Volunteer Infantry Regiment and a battalion of US Marines.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] These units were ordered to support two batteries of cannon on the Federal right flank led by Captains Charles Griffin and James B.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] The 11th New York and 1st Minnesota were directed into position at the top of Henry House Hill by Major William Farquhar Barry, McDowell's chief of artillery, and ordered to assault the Confederate line.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] On the initial confrontation with the 33rd Virginia Infantry on the left of Confederate General Thomas J.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] "Stonewall" Jackson's line, both the Union and Confederate forces were initially confused because the some of 11th New York were wearing several colors of shirts and the Virginians were clad in dark blue frock coats and dark blue trousers.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] The Virginians fired a volley that took down several men and the Zouaves and Marines broke and ran, but a few of the men remained.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] As the 11th New York and 1st Minnesota were regrouping along the Manassas-Sudley Road, they were encountered by Confederate Colonel J.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] Stuart mistook the New Yorkers for retreating Confederates in the smoke and quickly rode forward, shouting, "Don't run, boys; we are here." But after seeing a color bearer passing with the United States flag, he realized his mistake.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] Stuart ordered a small band of "Black Horse" cavalry, led by R.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] Welby Carter and the men of his Loudoun Company, to charge from the right and strike the 11th's rear guard.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] The 11th New York saw them coming and shifted formations to meet Carter's men.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] The 11th's volleys quickly killed eight of the riders and wounded nine with the rest escaping back into the woods; the charge had little effect on the organization of Fire Zouaves.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] While repulsing the cavalry charge, Colonel Farnham was wounded, but remained on the field aided by Lt.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] By 2:00 p.m., the 11th New York and 1st Minnesota were joined by the 14th Brooklyn Regiment and again took their place behind the Union guns.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] However, soon confusion again erupted on the battlefield in front of them.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] As the gunners confronted the blue-clad 33rd Virginia, Major Barry ordered Ricketts to hold his fire, allowing the Virginians to charge the batteries and capture the guns.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] While the 14th Brooklyn was able to quickly retake the guns, the Union regiments supporting the cannon were unable to withstand the near constant barrage from Confederate artillery and infantry and fell back again to the Manassas-Sudley Road.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] The 11th New York, the Irish 69th New York Militia and 14th Brooklyn would charge Henry Hill four times, first in an effort to retake Ricketts' and Griffin's cannon, but each attempt failed.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] In the wild melee, the 69th's color bearers were killed and its colors lost, but an officer of the 11th, Captain John Wildey, was able to recapture the Irish color, and then handed it back to the grateful Irishmen.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] When the order to withdraw from the field came later that evening from General McDowell, the 11th New York served as a rearguard.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] It was during this retreat that the regiment saw its heaviest casualties.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] Although accounts of the battle differ, most sources list 177 men lost at Bull Run, with 35 men killed, 74 wounded, and another 68 missing and presumed captured.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] Those that were taken prisoner were initially confined in Richmond.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] In September, they were transferred to Castle Pinckney, South Carolina, where they remained until they were paroled the following May.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] On August 12, 1861, the remaining members of the regiment were sent back to New York City to disband, in preparation to reorganize, obtain equipment and replacements.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] On September 14, 1861, after reorganizing, they were ordered by Governor Edwin D.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] Morgan, at the request of Secretary of War Simon Cameron, to return to Virginia with two days' cooked rations.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] They were to be encamped at Fort Monroe on the tip of the Virginia Peninsula.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] An entry from January 31, 1862, of the Official Records places the 11th New York as a unit of the Department of Virginia at Camp Butler under the command of Brig.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] On March 8, 1862, they watched from shore as the USS *Monitor* and CSS *Virginia* dueled off the coast of Hampton Roads.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] Two members of the regiment were detailed to the nearby USS *Cumberland* and manned its cannons until they were forced to abandon ship.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] With manpower further depleted as a result of injury and disease, the regiment was returned to New York City on May 7.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] There, it was mustered out of service on June 2, 1862.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] Burke received authority to reorganize the original regiment as a three-years regiment to be known as the *J.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] Burke was required to raise 250 men for the effort but failed.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] His authorization was revoked on June 7 and transferred to Colonel Henry F.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] O'Brien was required to raise 250 men by August 1, 250 others by September 1, and an additional 250 men by November 1.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] These recruiting efforts were hampered by the draft riot in New York City of July 1863.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] As the 11th New York Regiment had experienced first hand, the First Battle of Bull Run in July 1861 had taken a heavy toll on Union forces, including those from New York City.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] As the war dragged on, a military manpower shortage occurred in the Union and Congress passed the first conscription act in United States history on March 3, 1863, authorizing the President to draft male citizens between the ages of 18 and 35 for a three-year term of military service.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] Initially intended to express anger at the draft, the protests deteriorated into "a virtual racial pogrom, with uncounted numbers of blacks murdered on the streets".
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] The conditions in the city were such that Major General John E.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] Wool stated on July 16, "Martial law ought to be proclaimed, but I have not a sufficient force to enforce it".
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] States' militias and Federal troops attached to the Army of the Potomac, including the newly reorganized 11th New York, were dispatched to quell the riots.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] Other regiments utilized included the 152nd New York, the 26th Michigan, the 27th Indiana and the 7th Regiment New York State Militia, which arrived from Frederick, Maryland after a forced march.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] In addition, New York governor Horatio Seymour sent the 74th and 65th regiments of the New York state militia, which had not been federalized, and a section of the 20th Artillery from Fort Schuyler in Throgs Neck.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] At the height of the violence, Colonel O'Brien, the 11th Regiment's commanding officer, was seized by the mob, beaten, and killed.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] In the wake of the riots, the reorganization produced few recruits and stalled.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] On October 1, 1863, the reorganization was discontinued and the men who had enlisted were transferred to the 17th New York Veteran Volunteer Infantry Regiment.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] During its limited but intense combat experience, the regiment saw 51 members killed, including three officers and 48 enlisted men.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] Among these was the regiment's first commander, Colonel Elmer E.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] Ellsworth, who was the first conspicuous casualty of the Civil War.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] Brownell became the first soldier in the Civil War to be awarded the Medal of Honor for his actions in killing Col.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] Following Ellsworth's death, *Remember Ellsworth!* and *Avenge Ellsworth* became Union rallying cries.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] The 44th New York Volunteer Infantry Regiment was raised by the *People's Ellsworth Committee* and were known as the "People's Ellsworth Regiment", or more commonly "Ellsworth's Avengers", under the command of Stephen W.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] Stryker, a former lieutenant in the 11th New York.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] Apart from those who died of battle wounds, three officers and 12 enlisted men succumbed to disease, including its second colonel, Noah Farnham, who died as a result of his wounds sustained at Bull Run and a bout of typhoid.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] A total of 66 men of the 11th New York Infantry Regiment died in the course of the war.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] In 1903, the flag for which Ellsworth gave his life, taken down from the top of Marshal House, was presented to the War Department by its custodian, the Ellsworth Post, Grand Army of the Republic.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] The flag had been carried by the regiment throughout the war and afterward maintained at their post headquarters.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] It was added to the war flag collection in Cullum Memorial Hall at West Point.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] Historian David Detzer has argued that the fame that surrounds the 11th New York is misplaced.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] During its time in service, the 11th New York Regiment saw little fighting compared with other well-known regiments such as the 69th New York, 20th Maine, and 28th Massachusetts.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] The 11th New York was often overshadowed by the 73rd New York, also known as the Second Fire Zouaves, which fought at Antietam, Gettysburg, and Appomattox.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] In addition, Ellsworth failed to consider that the New York City fire companies from which his troops were drawn often competed against each other at blazes.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] The cohesion he sought in firefighters did not exist and would not be created when they joined the regiment.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] In that respect, 11th New York was no different from many regiments, North and South.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] Regiment lost during service 3 Officers and 48 Enlisted men killed and mortally wounded and 3 Officers and 12 Enlisted men by disease.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] The regiment's bloodiest battle was First Bull Run.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] Throughout its service, the regiment was armed with National Armory (NA) manufactured model 1855 rifle-muskets drawn from state arsenals.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] Like most Zouave regiments, the men of the 11th New York were fashioned in uniforms not typical of the standard ensemble of a Union soldier.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] During their service, the 11th New York wore two different style of uniforms, the first issued during the forming of the regiment and the second shortly before the Battle of Bull Run.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] The initial uniforms were purchased with funds donated by the Union Defense Committee.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] They were based on Ellsworth's own design.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] They consisted of light gray jackets of a chasseur style, with dark blue and red trim along with gray trousers of a jeans cloth material with a blue stripe running down the seam, and tan leather leggings.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] Along with their gray uniforms, they wore red kepis with a blue band and also received a red fez with a blue tassel, military-issue shirt and/or overshirts.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] Many Zouaves went off to war wearing the fire badge of their respective fire company.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] Contrary to modern art prints, the Fire Zouaves did not go off to war wearing fireman's belts or paint mottos on their fezzes.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] The second uniform was issued when the first, not made of quality materials, fell apart on most men.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] This uniform was issued by the federal government, and to the disgust of the men, was not of the true Zouave style, but an American Zouave style.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] The new uniform had a dark blue Zouave jacket with red cuffs and red trimming with sky blue trimming inside the red.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] Blue fezzes with blue tassels were issued to provide greater flair to the uniform, as well as dark blue sashes, an issue of red overshirts (not firemen's shirts), and dark blue trousers.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] Before the First Battle of Bull Run, most of the Zouaves left their jackets in camp due to the July heat, however, they all retained their blue and red fezzes, and their red blue banded kepis.
[src:alexandria-virginia/11th-new-york-volunteer-infantry-regiment] A number of havelocks were also issued to the regiment.
[src:alexandria-virginia/14th-century] The **14th century** lasted from 1 January 1301 (represented by the Roman numerals MCCCI) to 31 December 1400 (MCD).
[src:alexandria-virginia/14th-century] It is estimated that the century witnessed the death of more than 45 million lives from political and natural disasters in both Europe and the Mongol Empire.
[src:alexandria-virginia/14th-century] West Africa experienced economic growth and prosperity.
[src:alexandria-virginia/14th-century] This period is considered the height of chivalry and marks the beginning of strong separate identities for both England and France as well as the foundation of the Italian Renaissance and the Ottoman Empire.
[src:alexandria-virginia/14th-century] In Asia, Tamerlane (Timur), established the Timurid Empire, history's third largest empire to have been ever established by a single conqueror.
[src:alexandria-virginia/14th-century] Scholars estimate that Timur's military campaigns caused the deaths of 17 million people, amounting to about 5% of the world population at the time.
[src:alexandria-virginia/14th-century] Synchronously, the Timurid Renaissance emerged.
[src:alexandria-virginia/14th-century] In the Arab world, historian and political scientist Ibn Khaldun and explorer Ibn Battuta made significant contributions.
[src:alexandria-virginia/14th-century] In India, the Bengal Sultanate separated from the Delhi Sultanate, a major trading nation in the world.
[src:alexandria-virginia/14th-century] The sultanate was described by the Europeans as the richest country to trade with.
[src:alexandria-virginia/14th-century] The Mongol court was driven out of China and retreated to Mongolia, the Ilkhanate collapsed, the Chaghatayid dissolved and broke into two parts, and the Golden Horde lost its position as a great power in Eastern Europe.
[src:alexandria-virginia/14th-century] In Africa, the wealthy Mali Empire, a huge producer of gold, reached its territorial and economic height under the reign of Mansa Musa I of Mali, the wealthiest individual of medieval times, and perhaps the wealthiest ever.
[src:alexandria-virginia/14th-century] In the Americas, the Mexica founded the city of Tenochtitlan, while the Mississippian mound city of Cahokia was abandoned.
[src:alexandria-virginia/1790-united-states-census] The **1790 United States census** was the first United States census.
[src:alexandria-virginia/1790-united-states-census] It recorded the population of the whole United States as of Census Day, August 2, 1790, as mandated by Article 1, Section 2, of the Constitution and applicable laws.
[src:alexandria-virginia/1790-united-states-census] In the first census, the population of the United States was enumerated to be 3,929,214 inhabitants.
[src:alexandria-virginia/1790-united-states-census] Congress assigned responsibility for the 1790 census to the marshals of United States judicial districts under an act, which with minor modifications and extensions, governed census taking through the 1840 census.
[src:alexandria-virginia/1790-united-states-census] Both Secretary of State Thomas Jefferson and President George Washington expressed skepticism over the results, believing that the true population had been undercounted.
[src:alexandria-virginia/1790-united-states-census] If indeed an undercount was the result, possible explanations for it include dispersed population, poor transportation links, limitations of contemporary technology, and individual refusal to participate.
[src:alexandria-virginia/1790-united-states-census] Although the census was proved statistically factual, based on data collected, the records for several states (including Delaware, Georgia, New Jersey, and Virginia) were lost sometime between 1790 and 1830.
[src:alexandria-virginia/1790-united-states-census] Almost one-third of the original census data have been lost or destroyed since their original documentation.
[src:alexandria-virginia/1790-united-states-census] No microdata from the 1790 population census are available, but aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:alexandria-virginia/1790-united-states-census] The census was not conducted in Vermont until 1791, after that state's admission to the Union as the 14th state on March 4 of that year.
[src:alexandria-virginia/1790-united-states-census] At 17.8 percent, the 1790 census's proportion of slaves to the free population was the highest ever recorded by any census of the United States.
[src:alexandria-virginia/1790-united-states-census] 0 is the correct figure, and the 16 here should be added to the "All other free persons" column.
[src:alexandria-virginia/1790-united-states-census] When the census of 1790 was published in 1791, it reported 16 slaves, which were illegal in Vermont.
[src:alexandria-virginia/1790-united-states-census] Subsequently, and up to 1860, the number is given as 17.
[src:alexandria-virginia/1790-united-states-census] An examination of the original manuscript by the Census Bureau superintendent found that there never were any slaves in Vermont.
[src:alexandria-virginia/1790-united-states-census] The original error occurred in preparing the results for publication, when 16 persons, returned as "Free colored," were classified as "Slave" in Bennington County.
[src:alexandria-virginia/1790-united-states-census] Corrected figures are 85,425, or 114 less than figures published in 1790, due to an error of addition of several towns.
[src:alexandria-virginia/1790-united-states-census] Corrected figures are 59,096, or 2 more than figures published in 1790, due to error in addition.
[src:alexandria-virginia/1790-united-states-census] The figures for Virginia do not include the population of Kentucky.
[src:alexandria-virginia/1790-united-states-census] Though Kentucky was then a part of Virginia, the Kentucky figures were compiled separately, and are shown on the line for Kentucky.
[src:alexandria-virginia/1790-united-states-census] The Virginia figures do include the portion of Virginia that later became the state of West Virginia.
[src:alexandria-virginia/1800-united-states-census] The **1800 United States census** was the second census conducted in the United States.
[src:alexandria-virginia/1800-united-states-census] It showed that 5,308,483 people were living in the United States, of whom 893,602 were slaves.
[src:alexandria-virginia/1800-united-states-census] The 1800 census included the new District of Columbia.
[src:alexandria-virginia/1800-united-states-census] The census for the following states were lost: Georgia, Kentucky, New Jersey, Tennessee, and Virginia.
[src:alexandria-virginia/1800-united-states-census] In comparison to the 1790 census, the 1800 census gathered additional information.
[src:alexandria-virginia/1800-united-states-census] The census was published in December 1801 and cost $66,109.04.
[src:alexandria-virginia/1800-united-states-census] This census is one of the several for which some of the original data are no longer available.
[src:alexandria-virginia/1800-united-states-census] Original census returns for Georgia, Kentucky, Mississippi, New Jersey, Tennessee, and Virginia were lost over the years.
[src:alexandria-virginia/1800-united-states-census] No microdata from the 1800 population census are available, but aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:alexandria-virginia/1810-united-states-census] The **1810 United States census** was the third census conducted in the United States.
[src:alexandria-virginia/1810-united-states-census] It showed that 7,239,881 people were living in the United States, of whom 1,191,362 were slaves.
[src:alexandria-virginia/1810-united-states-census] The 1810 census included one new state: Ohio.
[src:alexandria-virginia/1810-united-states-census] The original census returns for the District of Columbia, Georgia, Mississippi, New Jersey, and Ohio were lost or destroyed over the years.
[src:alexandria-virginia/1810-united-states-census] Most of Tennessee's original forms were also lost, other than Grainger and Rutherford counties.
[src:alexandria-virginia/1810-united-states-census] This was the last census with Virginia ranked as the most populous state.
[src:alexandria-virginia/1810-united-states-census] Census taking was not yet an exact science.
[src:alexandria-virginia/1810-united-states-census] Before 1830, enumerators lacked pre-printed forms, and some drew up their own, resulting in pages without headings.
[src:alexandria-virginia/1810-united-states-census] Some enumerators did not tally their results.
[src:alexandria-virginia/1810-united-states-census] As a result, census records for many towns before 1830 are idiosyncratic.
[src:alexandria-virginia/1810-united-states-census] This is not to suggest that they are less reliable than subsequent censuses, but that they may require more work on the part of the researcher.
[src:alexandria-virginia/1810-united-states-census] No microdata from the 1810 population census are available, but aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:alexandria-virginia/1820-united-states-census] The **1820 United States census** was the fourth census conducted in the United States.
[src:alexandria-virginia/1820-united-states-census] The 1820 census included six new states: Louisiana, Indiana, Mississippi, Illinois, Alabama and Maine.
[src:alexandria-virginia/1820-united-states-census] There has been a district wide loss of 1820 census records for Arkansas Territory, Missouri Territory, and New Jersey.
[src:alexandria-virginia/1820-united-states-census] The total population was determined to be 9,638,453, of which 1,538,022 were slaves.
[src:alexandria-virginia/1820-united-states-census] The center of population was about 120 miles (193 km) west-northwest of Washington in Hardy County, Virginia (now in West Virginia).
[src:alexandria-virginia/1820-united-states-census] This was the first census in which any states recorded a population of over one million—New York, Virginia, and Pennsylvania—as well as the first in which a city recorded a population of over 100,000—New York.
[src:alexandria-virginia/1820-united-states-census] Also, in this census and the 14 subsequent ones, New York was the most populous state until being superseded by California in the 1970 census.
[src:alexandria-virginia/1820-united-states-census] The 1820 census contains a great deal more information than previous censuses.
[src:alexandria-virginia/1820-united-states-census] Several of these columns were for special counts, and not to be included in the aggregate total.
[src:alexandria-virginia/1820-united-states-census] Doing so would have resulted in counting some individuals twice.
[src:alexandria-virginia/1820-united-states-census] Census takers were asked to use double lines, red ink or some other method of distinguishing these columns so that double counting would not occur.
[src:alexandria-virginia/1820-united-states-census] For example, the count of free white males between 16 and 18 was a special count, because these individuals were also supposed to be tabulated in the column for free white males of age 16 and under 26.
[src:alexandria-virginia/1820-united-states-census] The other special counts were foreigners not naturalized, persons engaged in agriculture, persons engaged in commerce, and persons engaged in manufacture.
[src:alexandria-virginia/1820-united-states-census] Census takers were also instructed to count each individual in only one of the occupational columns.
[src:alexandria-virginia/1820-united-states-census] For example, if an individual was engaged in agriculture, commerce, and manufacture, the census taker had to judge which one the individual was primarily engaged in.
[src:alexandria-virginia/1820-united-states-census] Before 1830, enumerators lacked pre-printed forms, and drew up their own, sometimes resulting in pages without headings, line tallies, or column totals.
[src:alexandria-virginia/1830-united-states-census] The **1830 United States census**, the fifth census undertaken in the United States, was conducted on June 1, 1830.
[src:alexandria-virginia/1830-united-states-census] The only loss of census records for 1830 involved some countywide losses in Massachusetts, Maryland, and Mississippi.
[src:alexandria-virginia/1830-united-states-census] It determined the population of the 24 states to be 12,866,020, of which 2,009,043 were slaves.
[src:alexandria-virginia/1830-united-states-census] The center of population was about 170 miles (274 km) west of Washington, D.C. in present-day Grant County, West Virginia.
[src:alexandria-virginia/1830-united-states-census] This was the first census in which a city—New York—recorded a population of over 200,000.
[src:alexandria-virginia/1830-united-states-census] No microdata from the 1830 population census are available, but aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] Alexandria was established in 1749 and incorporated as a town in 1779.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] In its early decades, Alexandria's port was one of the largest in the country, prospering from the trade of agricultural goods and slaves.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] Ceded to the District of Columbia in 1801, economic troubles led to Alexandria's retrocession back to Virginia in 1847.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] Alexandria was re-chartered as a city in 1852 and became independent of Alexandria County in 1870.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] The 19th century saw Alexandria become a manufacturing and railway hub as its port declined in importance.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] The city significantly expanded its borders in the 20th century, particularly with the annexation of the town of Potomac and its surroundings in 1930 and an unincorporated portion of Fairfax County in 1952, both of which roughly doubled Alexandria's land area.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] The highest-income independent city in Virginia, Alexandria is heavily influenced by its proximity to the national capital.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] The expansion of the U.S. federal government during the New Deal and World War II, coupled with postwar deindustrialization, helped transform Alexandria into a community for federal employees.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] The city's largest employers include the U.S.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] Department of Defense's Mark Center and the U.S.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] Numerous nonprofit organizations and private corporations are also headquartered in Alexandria.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] Tourism is a major industry, particularly in the city's traditional core of Old Town.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] Old Town hosts the Alexandria Historic District, the third historic district in the United States.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] According to archaeologists' estimates, a succession of indigenous peoples began to occupy the Chesapeake and Tidewater region about 3,000 to 10,000 years ago.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] Various Algonquian-speaking peoples inhabited the lands in the Potomac River drainage area since at least the early 14th century.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] On this visit, Smith recorded the presence of a settlement called *Assaomeck* near the south bank of what is now Hunting Creek.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] On October 21, 1669, a patent granted 6,000 acres (24 km2) to Robert Howsing for transporting 120 people to the Colony of Virginia; this land would eventually become Alexandria.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] Virginia's comprehensive Tobacco Inspection Law of 1730 mandated that all tobacco grown in the colony must be brought to locally designated public warehouses for inspection before sale.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] One of the sites designated for a warehouse on the upper Potomac River was at the mouth of Hunting Creek.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] After the original site south of the creek was deemed "very inconvenient", the warehouse was built at West's Point to the north.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] This land had been given to John Alexander and Hugh West by John's father Robert Alexander.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] Robert's cousin, Philip Alexander, owned a 500 acres (2.0 km2) estate to the south, which was bounded by Hunting Creek, Hooff's Run, the Potomac River, and the future Cameron Street.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] In 1742, Fairfax County was split from Prince William County.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] Local planters and merchants, including Thomas Fairfax and Lawrence Washington, sought to establish a port for the new county.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] At the opening of Virginia's 1748–49 legislative session, the House of Burgesses received a petition on November 1, 1748 that stated that the "inhabitants of Fairfax (Co.) praying that a town may be established at Hunting Creek Warehouse on Potowmack River".
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] Lawrence's younger brother George Washington, an aspiring surveyor, made a sketch of the shoreline touting the advantages of the tobacco warehouse site.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] Opponents of the warehouse site submitted a petition asking for the small settlement of Cameron along Hunting Creek to be selected instead.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] Both of these original petitions were rejected by the House of Burgesses.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] On May 2, 1749, the House of Burgesses approved the river location and ordered "Mr.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] Washington do go up with a Message to the Council and acquaint them that this House have agreed to the Amendments titled An Act for erecting a Town at Hunting Creek Warehouse, in the County of Fairfax".
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] A "Public Vendue" (auction) was advertised for July, and the county surveyor laid out street lanes and town lots.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] The auction was conducted on July 13–14, 1749.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] The Fairfax County Court began meeting in Alexandria's Market Square in 1752.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] The origin of the name "Alexandria" is not clearly documented.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] Alexandria's city government states that it was likely chosen to try to win the support of the Alexander family.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] If so, the effort failed, as Philip Alexander endorsed the Cameron site.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] The city government further connects the name to the Egyptian city of Alexandria, which would have appealed to the "classically educated elites of the day".
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] An alternative designation for the town was "Belhaven", with the first known use of the name being a 1749 plat entitled "A Plan of Alexandria now Belhaven".
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] The name was intended to honor Scottish anti-unionist John Hamilton, 2nd Lord Belhaven and Stenton, as "patriotic" Scottish merchants were active along the Potomac at the time.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] The name Belhaven was used in official lotteries to raise money for a church and market house.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] Though the alternative name did not find lasting success, some maps continued to label the town as Belhaven as late as 1783.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] In March 1755, Edward Braddock arrived in Alexandria with a force of about 1400 British regulars and 450 colonial troops as he prepared for operations against the French during the French and Indian War.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] There, he hosted a meeting with the governors of Virginia, Maryland, Pennsylvania, Massachusetts, and New York at Carlyle House to discuss the war.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] His army subsequently departed Alexandria for an expedition against Fort Duquesne that ended in Braddock's defeat and death against a French and Native American force.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] In 1774, the British closure of Boston Harbor prompted pro-Boston Alexandrians, including John Carlyle, to establish a committee of correspondence.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] On July 18 of that year, George Washington, George Mason, and other residents of Fairfax County met at Alexandria's Market Square to issue the Fairfax Resolves, which called for a congress of colonial representatives and a boycott of British goods.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] After the American Revolutionary War began in 1775, Alexandria remained sympathetic towards the revolutionaries, supplying the colonial military with troops and purging local Loyalists.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] The town was "virtually unscathed" by combat, but nonetheless was a hub of military activity, hosting a Hessian prisoner of war camp, numerous fortifications to defend against British attack, and a smallpox vaccination center for the Southern Department.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] The sale of grain and other foodstuffs to revolutionary troops and their French backers provided a significant boost to Alexandria's economy.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] The revolutionary government of Virginia began chartering and re-chartering many of its communities amidst the conflict.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] Under this effort, Alexandria was formally incorporated as a town in December 1779.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] The town's trustees were replaced by directly elected officials, including a six-man common council as well as a Court of Hustings consisting of a mayor, a recorder, and four aldermen.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] 1779 also saw Virginia designate Alexandria as an international port of entry with its own customs system.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] As the war came to a conclusion, Alexandria's export of flour and tobacco greatly increased.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] Trade with Europe, which was the destination of about half of the town's exports, was reestablished, while the West Indies served as another major customer of Alexandrian goods.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] A decline in tobacco production caused economic contraction in the late 1780s, but trade rapidly recovered in the 1790s.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] Alexandria was the dominant port along the Potomac by 1790 and was the seventh-largest port in the United States by 1796.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] In March 1785, commissioners from Virginia and Maryland met in Alexandria to discuss the commercial relations of the two states, finishing their business at Mount Vernon.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] The Mount Vernon Conference concluded on March 28 with an agreement for freedom of trade and freedom of navigation of the Potomac River.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] The Maryland legislature, in ratifying this agreement on November 22, proposed a conference among representatives from all the states to consider the adoption of definite commercial regulations.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] This led to the calling of the Annapolis Convention of 1786, which in turn led to the calling of the Federal Convention of 1787.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] As the United States began planning for the creation of a new federal capital city, Virginia passed an act on December 3, 1789 that approved the cession of up to 10 square miles of territory to the proposed capital.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] The Residence Act of 1790 authorized the creation of a federal capital along the Potomac River, with its exact borders to be determined by George Washington.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] Washington insisted upon Alexandria's inclusion in the new city, which was approved in an amendment to the act in 1791.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] That year, the first and southernmost boundary marker of the capital was erected at Alexandria's Jones Point.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] Ahead of Alexandria's expected cession, the Fairfax County Court moved to Fairfax City in April 1800.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] The District of Columbia was organized under the District of Columbia Organic Act of 1801, formally splitting Alexandria from Virginia and placing it within the new Alexandria County alongside the remainder of Virginia's cession.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] With their inclusion in the new capital, Alexandrians lost Virginia state citizenship as well as the right to vote in federal elections.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] Alexandria continued to operate under Virginia law until 1804, when Congress granted a new charter for the town that abolished the positions of recorder and alderman, expanded the common council to 16 members, and divided the town into four wards.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] In 1814, during the War of 1812, the British military carried out a successful raid on Alexandria, which surrendered without a fight.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] In order to avoid the town's destruction, twenty-two merchant ships and large quantities of flour, tobacco, cotton, wine, and sugar were handed over by Alexandria's municipal authorities to the British.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] Alexandria's economy stagnated with a decline in Northern Virginia's agricultural output, and the slave trade became increasingly important as Alexandria sought to supply the cotton industry of the Deep South.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] Even as "observers perceived the downward trend of Alexandria's relative economic power", Alexandria grew to become the country's largest center of slave trading by the 1830s.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] From 1828 to 1836, Alexandria was home to the Franklin & Armfield Slave Market, one of the largest slave trading companies in the United States.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] By the 1830s, they were sending more than 1,000 slaves annually from Alexandria to their Natchez, Mississippi, New Orleans, and later Texas markets to help meet the demand for slaves in Mississippi and nearby states.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] As discontent with the District of Columbia grew south of the Potomac, a movement emerged that called for Alexandria County to be retroceded to Virginia.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] Amidst economic troubles, many in Alexandria felt neglected by Congress, which Alexandrians had no say in due to the disenfranchisement of District residents.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] As the Chesapeake & Ohio (C&O) Canal spurred development on the north side of the Potomac, Alexandria invested heavily into its own canal to provide a direct connection to the C&O Canal's terminus at Georgetown, which failed to provide the desired economic benefits despite the steep cost.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] Meanwhile, Georgetown's port emerged as a major rival to Alexandria's.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] Alexandria was also ineligible to host federal buildings under the 1791 amendment to the Residence Act.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] Further, proposals to abolish the slave trade in the District would have devastated one of Alexandria's major industries.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] Pro-slavery factions in Virginia likewise wanted the land to be returned to provide the state legislature with an additional two members that would likely favor slavery.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] On July 9, 1846, Congress agreed to hold a referendum in Alexandria County on the issue of retrocession.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] On September 1 and 2, 763 voted in favor of retrocession while 222 opposed it.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] Polk accepted the results on September 7, and Virginia formally assumed control over the land on March 13, 1847.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] Alexandria was re-chartered as a city in 1852.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] Alexandria's port, the ninth-largest in the nation in 1847, remained a valuable asset, but the town sought to diversify its economy with an industrialization effort after leaving the District.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] Despite its financial burdens, the Alexandria Canal helped provide coal and raw materials that were useful for the development of industry.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] Having returned to Virginia, Alexandria was also no longer subject to the financial regulations that Congress imposed upon the District.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] Alexandria soon became a significant railway hub, beginning with the founding of the Orange and Alexandria Railroad in 1848 and continuing with the Manassas Gap Railroad in 1850 and the Alexandria, Loudoun, & Hampshire Railroad in 1854.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] The manufacturing industry expanded as numerous machine shops and foundries were established, and by 1850, Alexandria's richest man was a manufacturer rather than a merchant.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] Alexandria's Whig leadership, which had dominated local politics since the 1830s, also made significant investments in public works during this period, greatly improving its infrastructure.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] In the 1860 presidential election, Alexandria supported Constitutional Union Party candidate John Bell.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] As talk of secession grew in early 1861, Alexandria continued to support the Union, sending Unionist George William Brent as its representative to a Virginia convention on secession in February.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] After the Civil War began in earnest with the Battle of Fort Sumter, Alexandria rapidly came to oppose remaining in the Union.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] On May 23, 958 Alexandrians voted to approve Virginia's secession, while 106 voted against.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] The following day, Union troops landed at the base of Cameron Street, hoping to secure the city's rail network and port.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] Ellsworth of the New York Fire Zouaves removed a large Confederate flag from the roof of the Marshall House, for which he was shot and killed by proprietor James W.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] The deaths of Ellsworth and Jackson were widely publicized, and both men became martyrs for their respective sides.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] Alexandria was the subject of the longest Union occupation of any settlement in the country during the Civil War, remaining under military control for the duration of the conflict.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] The city became a major logistical hub for the Army of the Potomac, with many buildings seized for supply depots and medical centers.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] Fort Ward, one of a ring of forts built by the Union army for the defense of Washington, D.C., is located inside the boundaries of present-day Alexandria.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] There were five military prisons in the city, the largest being the Washington Street Military Prison.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] The war caused a steep increase in the city's black population due to the arrival of thousands of escaped slaves, designated "contrabands" to avoid returning them to their masters.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] The Restored Government of Virginia, the Unionist rival to Virginia's secessionist government, was headquartered in Alexandria from August 1863 until May 1865 after its previous stronghold became the new state of West Virginia.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] As Reconstruction began, Alexandria's population was roughly half black.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] With local Unionists and Republican carpetbaggers helping shape policy under military protection, these black residents experienced a brief period of enhanced rights.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] In 1869, Virginia was readmitted to the union with a new state constitution.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] Federal troops withdrew from the city on January 26, 1870, restoring civilian control.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] Alexandria subsequently became an independent city distinct from Alexandria County, as Virginia's new constitution stipulated that any city of at least 10,000 people would be independent.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] The city's black population, aligned with the local Republicans, gained the right to vote with the passage of the Fifteenth Amendment.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] The Conservative Party emerged as a serious rival to the Republicans, and the Conservative candidate won a narrow victory in the first post-war mayoral race on May 26, 1870.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] Nonetheless, that election also saw the first black man elected to city council, and a Republican was elected mayor in 1872.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] By the mid-1870s, however, the Democratic Party came to dominate city politics, pushing the Republicans and their African American supporters to the political fringe.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] The implementation of Jim Crow laws reversed many of the gains that black people had made after the war.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] Alexandria's economy struggled throughout much of the late 19th century.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] The Civil War had burdened the city with large numbers of refugees and numerous ruined structures, including its port, but debt from pre-war investments into railroads and canals limited its ability to fund recovery efforts.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] 1873 saw a milestone for transportation in the city with the opening of its first horse-drawn streetcar in July, but the Panic of 1873 further harmed the city's economy.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] An 1881 essay in *Scribner's Monthly* described Alexandria as "dead commercially".
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] The city's history of wooden shipbuilding came to an end around 1883 due to the expense of producing fittings elsewhere and delivering them to Alexandria.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] The Alexandria Canal brought in record amounts of coal, but its continuous failure to attain desired levels of profitability resulted in its permanent closure in 1887.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] Even as many East Coast cities experienced surges in immigration, Alexandria's population growth was negligible in the 1870s and 1880s, and the city had fallen far behind regional peers like Washington and Baltimore.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] The 1880s did see "modern conveniences" come to Alexandria, including telephone service in 1881 and electricity in 1889.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] The first electric streetcars arrived in Alexandria in 1892, fueling the growth of suburbs to the north and west of the city.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] In the waning years of the 19th century, Alexandria suffered its two documented lynchings.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] McCoy and the second, in 1899, was Benjamin Thomas.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] Both were Black male teenagers accused, but never convicted, of assaulting young white girls that were known to them.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] They were both kidnapped from jail and hanged by mobs.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] The early 1900s were a prosperous time for Alexandria's manufacturing industry, with Lynchburg being the only city in Virginia to experience a greater increase in production.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] Glass was among the city's most important products, with the Virginia Glass Company, the Alexandria Glass Company, Old Dominion Glass Company, and the Belle Pre Bottle Company emerging as prominent businesses in this sector.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] Other key products included fertilizer, beer, and leather.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] Most businesses were relatively small, with the business occupying the first floor of a building and the owner and family living above.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] In 1915, Alexandria annexed territory west of the city from Fairfax and Alexandria Counties, including the neighborhoods of Rosemont, Eisenhower East and Carlyle, and Shuter's Hill.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] Alexandria Union Station, established in 1905 to consolidate the city's passenger rail stations, was within the annexed land.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] Shuter's Hill soon hosted the George Washington National Masonic Memorial, which opened in 1932.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] America's need for vessels in World War I led to the establishment of the Virginia Shipbuilding Corporation in 1918, a massive shipyard at Jones Point.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] President Woodrow Wilson visited the shipyard on May 30, 1918 to drive the first rivet into the yard's first keel to be laid down, the SS *Gunston Hall*.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] While the yard was expected to employ thousands of men for the construction of a dozen ships, the war ended before any could be deployed.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] The shipyard was largely abandoned in the early 1920s after legal investigations were launched into its owner, businessman and fraudster Charles W.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] In 1930, Alexandria doubled in size by again annexing portions of Fairfax and Alexandria Counties, the latter of which had changed its name to Arlington County in 1920.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] The annexed land was bounded by the Little River Turnpike/Duke Street to the south, Quaker Lane to the west, and Four Mile Run to the north.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] This included the incorporated town of Potomac within Arlington County, a streetcar suburb that was formed in 1908 from the residential neighborhoods of Del Ray and St.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] These areas housed many workers of Potomac Yard, one of the largest rail yards on the East Coast.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] On August 28, 1939, African-American lawyer and Alexandria native Samuel Wilbert Tucker organized a sit-in at the city's library to protest its policy of racial segregation.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] This was among the first sit-in protests against segregation in the United States, establishing what would become a key tactic of the civil rights movement.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] The Robert Robinson Library, intended for the city's black population, opened the following year.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] The new library was converted into the Alexandria Black History Museum after desegregation.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] Urban renewal in Alexandria began in 1939 as the city sought to carry out the slum clearance provisions of the Housing Act of 1937.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] As part of this policy, multiple black or mixed-race neighborhoods were demolished and replaced with segregated public housing developments.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] In 1946, part of Alexandria's "Old Town" core was designated the Alexandria Historic District, the third historic district in the United States.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] Many buildings in this district were demolished in the 1960s as part of the urban renewal effort, leading to the emergence of a strong historic preservation movement that called for the protection of the city's old structures.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] Alexandria's final urban renewal project was completed in 1984.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] The New Deal and World War II brought large numbers of new residents to Alexandria as the federal government expanded.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] After the war, the city's old maritime and industrial economy faltered as the rise of large container ships rendered small river ports obsolete.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] As Alexandria's manufacturing base largely died out, the city sought to replace it with tourism, redeveloping its previously industrial waterfront into a recreational hub.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] Though Alexandria did attract some corporate offices, the city largely became a residential community for government employees.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] In October 1950, Alexandria filed a lawsuit to annex 7.65 square miles of Fairfax County, stating that the city needed room to expand and would be better equipped to provide utilities for the land's residents than the county.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] The suit was approved by the Supreme Court of Virginia on December 3, 1951.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] When the annexation took effect on January 1, 1952, Alexandria's land area again roughly doubled.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] The annexed territory was the site of the Virginia Theological Seminary, established in 1823 by William Holland Wilmer, Francis Scott Key, and other prominent Episcopalians.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] The land was "sparsely populated", however, hosting only 11,000 residents.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] The annexation was swiftly followed by the massive development of both single-family homes as well as large apartment buildings.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] The post-annexation development brought many new streets to the area, and the city passed an ordinance in 1953 that stipulated that new north-south streets should be named for Confederate military officers.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] On December 28, 1961, the original Woodrow Wilson Bridge opened as part of the Capital Beltway, connecting Alexandria with Oxon Hill, Maryland.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] On July 1, 1969, Alexandria agreed to have the proposed Washington Metro expand into the city.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] After extensive delays, the King Street, Braddock Road, and Eisenhower Avenue stations opened as Metro's first three stations in Alexandria on December 17, 1983.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] To reduce its reliance on the Metrobus network, Alexandria opened its own bus transit system, DASH, on March 12, 1984.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] Metro's Van Dorn Street station opened in 1991.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] In 1971, Alexandria enacted a "K-6, 2, 2, 2 plan" in an attempt to racially "balance" the student population throughout the city's public schools to better reflect its racial makeup.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] Students were assigned to schools in grade-based groups, beginning with kindergarten through sixth grade, then seventh and eighth, then freshman and sophomore classes, and finally junior and senior classes.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] That same year, Herman Boone joined T.C.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] Williams High School, which all junior and senior students had been reassigned to, and lead the football team to a 13–0 season, a state championship, and a national championship runner-up, which was the basis for the 2000 film *Remember the Titans*.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] In 1973, Nora Lamborne and Beverly Beidler became the first women elected to the city council.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] In 1974, the Torpedo Factory Art Center opened.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] In 1991, Patricia Ticer became the first woman to be elected mayor.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] Changes in railroad technology reduced the utility of Potomac Yard as a rail hub.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] Alexandria 20/20, a joint venture between the Richmond, Fredericksburg and Potomac Railroad and CSX, announced in September 1988 that it would be pursuing plans to redevelop the railyard into a mixed-use community.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] The project, which was intended to be built over the course of 30 years, aimed to be the "largest ever development" in Alexandria's history.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] The site was an unsuccessful contender for a new Washington Redskins stadium in 1992.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] A strip mall opened in Potomac Yard in 1997, which was intended to only last for 20 years until the mixed-use housing and office development could materialize.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] The city repealed its policy of naming new north-south streets for Confederate officers in 2014.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] Route 1 in Alexandria was changed from Jefferson Davis Highway to Richmond Highway.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] Amidst the George Floyd protests, support grew for renaming Alexandria's T.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] Williams High School and Matthew Maury Elementary School, which were named for a segregationist school superintendent and a Confederate pro-slavery activist, respectively.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] The school board unanimously voted to rename both schools in November 2020, with the high school becoming Alexandria City High School and Maury Elementary becoming Naomi L.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] Brooks Elementary School on July 1, 2021.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] In 2023, Mayor Justin Wilson proposed renaming streets named for Confederates, beginning a phased process by which three to five streets would be renamed per phase.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] In May 2023, a Metro station opened at Potomac Yard, roughly 30 years after such a station was first proposed for the redeveloped community.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] By that time, some housing had been built in addition to the existing retail, but the neighborhood was "clearly still under development", with full development not expected for several years or decades.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] In December of that year, Virginia Governor Glenn Youngkin and Monumental Sports & Entertainment founder Ted Leonsis announced plans to develop a 70-acre area in Potomac Yard that would have featured a new arena for the Washington Capitals and Washington Wizards.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] The proposal failed in March 2024 after it did not advance in the Virginia General Assembly, with Monumental instead keeping its teams in Washington, D.C.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] An "Innovation Campus" for Virginia Tech opened at Potomac Yard in January 2025.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] Census Bureau, the city has a total area of 15.5 square miles (40.1 km2), of which 15.0 square miles (38.9 km2) is land and 0.42 square miles (1.1 km2), or 2.85%, is water.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] Alexandria is bounded on the east by the Potomac River (which forms the boundary between the city and Washington, D.C. and Prince George's County, Maryland), on the north and northwest by Arlington County, and on the south by Fairfax County.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] The western portions of the city were annexed from those two entities beginning in the 1930s.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] The addressing system in Alexandria is not uniform and reflects the consolidation of several originally separate communities into a single city.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] In Old Town Alexandria, building numbers are assigned north and south from King Street and west (only) from the Potomac River.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] In the areas formerly in the town of Potomac, such as Del Ray and St.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] Elmo, building numbers are assigned east and west from Commonwealth Avenue and north (only) from King Street.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] In the western parts of the city, building numbers are assigned north and south from Duke Street.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] The ZIP Code prefix 223 uniquely identifies the Alexandria postal area.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] However, the Alexandria postal area extends into Fairfax County and includes addresses outside of the city.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] Part of the George Washington Memorial Parkway is the one national protected area within the borders of Alexandria.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] As of 2024, the City of Alexandria is divided into 19 "Small Area Plans" and 11 additional overlapping plans.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] Some refer to these areas as Lower Alexandria, South Alexandria, or Alexandria, Fairfax County.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] The climate in this area is characterized by hot, humid summers and generally mild to cool winters.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] According to the Köppen climate classification system, Alexandria has a humid subtropical climate, abbreviated "Cfa" on climate maps.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] Note: the US Census treats Hispanic/Latino as an ethnic category.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] This table excludes Latinos from the racial categories and assigns them to a separate category.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] As of the 2020 census, Alexandria had a population of 159,467.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] 18.5% of residents were under the age of 18 and 11.8% of residents were 65 years of age or older.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] For every 100 females there were 90.8 males, and for every 100 females age 18 and over there were 88.0 males age 18 and over.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] 100.0% of residents lived in urban areas, while 0.0% lived in rural areas.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] There were 75,555 households in Alexandria, of which 22.7% had children under the age of 18 living in them.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] Of all households, 35.9% were married-couple households, 22.8% were households with a male householder and no spouse or partner present, and 34.4% were households with a female householder and no spouse or partner present.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] About 41.5% of all households were made up of individuals and 9.1% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] There were 80,479 housing units, of which 6.1% were vacant.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] The homeowner vacancy rate was 0.9% and the rental vacancy rate was 6.0%.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] At the 2010 census, there were 139,966 people, 68,082 households and 30,978 families residing in the city.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] The population density was 8,452.0 inhabitants per square mile (3,263.3/km2).
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] There were 68,082 housing units at an average density of 4,233.2 per square mile (1,634.4/km2).
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] In 2000, there were 61,889 households, of which 18.6% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 32.2% were married couples living together, 9.2% had a female householder with no husband present, and 55.2% were non-families.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] 43.4% of all households were made up of individuals, and 6.8% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] The average household size was 2.04 and the average family size was 2.87.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] For every 100 females, there were 93.5 males.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] For every 100 females aged 18 and over, there were 91.7 males.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] According to 2024 American Community Survey 1-Year Estimates, the median household income was $124,593 and median family income was $178,036.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] Additionally, 5.9% of the population of the population were below the poverty line.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] 5.6% of those under the age of 18 and 8.6% of those 65 and older were living below the poverty line.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] 69.4% of Alexandria residents aged 25 and older have attained a bachelor's degree or higher, compared with 43.3% statewide.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] Companies headquartered in Alexandria include Crooked Beat Records, Five Guys, the Institute for Defense Analyses (IDA), The Motley Fool, Oblon law firm, Pentagon Federal Credit Union (PenFed), Port City Brewing Company, Purple Strategies, ThinkFun, and VSE.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] Several federal agencies are based in Alexandria, including the National Credit Union Administration, United States Patent and Trademark Office, National Science Foundation, Department of Defense Office of Inspector General, and the Food and Nutrition Service.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] The Department of Defense Education Activity (DoDEA), the federal school system for military dependents, is headquartered in Alexandria.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] Alexandria is home to many charities and non-profit organizations including the national headquarters of Catholic Charities, Citizens for the Republic, Global Impact, Good360, International Centre for Missing & Exploited Children, Islamic Relief USA, United Way, and Volunteers of America.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] Alexandria also has a Chamber of Commerce and other business associations including the West End Business Association, the Del Ray Business Association and the Old Town Business Association.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] Major employment sectors in Alexandria include management consulting, business and finance, office and administrative support, computer and mathematical, sales, and legal.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] Jobs in Alexandria are highly concentrated around the city's Metrorail stations, primarily in Old Town North and the Braddock Road area, Old Town, and Carlyle near the Eisenhower Avenue station, as well as along the I-395 corridor on the west side of the city.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] Tourism is a major sector in Alexandria, with revenue from visitors surpassing US$1,000,000,000 in 2024 for the first time in the city's history.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] In 2025, Visit Alexandria announced that it was developing the city's first-ever tourism master plan, which included efforts to attract visitors to neighborhoods outside of the traditional core of Old Town.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] Visit Alexandria stated that tourism supported over 5700 jobs in the city at the time.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] 13% of people that work in Alexandria live in the city, while 87% commute in, with 37% of those commuters being from Fairfax County.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] An additional 61,000 people commute out of Alexandria to work.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] 35% commute to Washington, D.C., and 29% commute to Fairfax County.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] As of March 2024, 2.0% of Alexandria residents are unemployed.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] A popular Christmas time attraction in Alexandria is the Scottish Christmas Walk, which was established in 1969.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] The event, which involves a parade through the center of Old Town Alexandria, celebrates the city's Scottish heritage, and is the centerpiece of a yearly holiday festival.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] It serves as a fundraiser for social services in Alexandria.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] Other parades in Old Town celebrate Saint Patrick's Day and the birthday of George Washington.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] Other annual events include the Red Cross Waterfront Festival in June, the city's birthday celebration with fireworks show in July, various ethnic heritage days at Tavern Square, and "First Night Alexandria" on New Year's Eve.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] These parades and other official events are typically led by Alexandria's town crier, who, often dressed in elaborately, by a tradition dating to the 18th century, in a red coat, breeches, black boots and a tricorne hat, welcomes participants.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] Landmarks within the city include the George Washington Masonic National Memorial (also known as the Masonic Temple) and Observation Deck, Christ Church, Gadsby's Tavern, Stabler-Leadbeater Apothecary Shop, John Carlyle House, Lee-Fendall House, Robert E.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] Lee's boyhood home, and the Alexandria City Hall with the adjacent Market Square.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] Other sites of historical interest in the city include Fort Ward Park and Museum, Phoenix Mill, and the Alexandria Canal lock re-creation at Canal Office Center.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] The Alexandria Black History Museum, Alexandria Archaeology Museum, and the Lyceum display various aspects of the city's history.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] The Torpedo Factory Art Center, located on the Old Town waterfront, is a former torpedo factory that now serves as an art center filled with independent art studios and exhibits.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] The Athenaeum is another center for the arts.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] Also located in Old Town is Little Theatre of Alexandria, a community theatre at 600 Wolfe Street.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] South of Old Town on the Potomac River is the Jones Point Light and the nearby south cornerstone of the original District of Columbia.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] Immediately west of Old Town is the United States Patent and Trademark Office which includes the *National Inventors Hall of Fame Museum*.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] The Birchmere is a concert hall that features musical acts as well as ethnic and comedic performers.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] In 1830, John Hollensbury's home in Alexandria was one of two homes directly bordering an alleyway that received a large amount of horse-drawn wagon traffic and loiterers.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] In order to prevent people from using the alleyway, Hollensbury constructed a 7 feet (2.1 m) wide, 25 feet (7.6 m) deep, 325-square-foot (30.2 m2), two-story home using the existing brick walls of the adjacent homes for the sides of the new home.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] The brick walls of the Hollensbury Spite House living room have gouges from wagon-wheel hubs; the house is still standing, and is occupied.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] The Oswald Durant Center in the Upper King Street neighborhood of the Old Town is named after Dr.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] Oswald Durant, one of the first African American doctors in Alexandria.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] Alexandria has two local weekly newspapers: the *Alexandria Gazette Packet* and the *Alexandria Times*.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] The *Alexandria Gazette* was once published in the city from 1834 to 1974.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] The city is home to the Alexandria Aces of the Cal Ripken Sr.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] The team's home field is Frank Mann Field.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] Alexandria had previously been home of one professional sports team, the Alexandria Dukes, a minor league baseball team which moved to Woodbridge in 1984 to become The Prince William Pirates (now known as the Fredericksburg Nationals).
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] Alexandria has over 900 acres (3.6 km2) of protected open space with 566 acres of city-owned park land and 11 recreation centers, of which Chinquapin Park is one of the largest.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] Chinquapin offers facilities for swimming, tennis, racquetball, and other sports.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] Additionally, on March 19, 2024, a year-round recreation center opened inside of the Minnie Howard campus of Alexandria City High School, with a competition size swimming pool and a therapeutic training pool.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] The city also organizes several sports leagues throughout the year including volleyball, softball and basketball.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] The city is home to Cameron Run Regional Park, operated by NOVA Parks, which includes a water park, a miniature golf course, and batting cages.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] NOVA Parks also operates the Winkler Botanical Preserve in the city's West End.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] A portion of the Mount Vernon Trail, a popular bike and jogging path, runs through Old Town near the Potomac River on its way from the Mount Vernon Estate to Roosevelt Island in Washington, D.C.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p01] There is also a largely unbroken line of parks stretching along the Alexandria waterfront.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p02] As an independent city of Virginia (as opposed to an incorporated town within a county), Alexandria derives its governing authority from the Virginia General Assembly using the Dillon Rule.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p02] In order to revise the power and structure of the city government, the city must request the General Assembly to amend the charter.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p02] The present charter was granted in 1950 and it has been amended in 1968, 1971, 1976, and 1982.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p02] Alexandria adopted a council-manager form of government by way of referendum in 1921.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p02] This type of government empowers the elected City Council to pass legislation and appoint the City Manager.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p02] The City Manager is responsible for overseeing the city's administration.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p02] The Mayor, who is chosen on a separate ballot, presides over meetings of the Council and serves as the ceremonial head of government.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p02] The Mayor does not have the power to veto Council action.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p02] Council members traditionally choose the person receiving the most votes in the election to serve as Vice Mayor.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p02] In the absence or disability of the Mayor, the Vice Mayor performs the mayoral duties.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p02] In 2024, the city has 55 boards and commissions to advise the City Council on major issues affecting the community.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p02] The majority of members are appointed by the City Council.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p02] In addition, Alexandria City Public Schools has a school board with nine members.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p02] Three are elected from each of the city's three school board districts.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p02] Alexandria has a circuit court and a general district court.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p02] The city also has a juvenile and domestic relations district court.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p02] All of these courts are located in the Alexandria Courthouse at 520 King Street.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p02] The city is also the site of the Alexandria Division of the United States District Court for the Eastern District of Virginia.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p02] In the Virginia General Assembly, Alexandria is represented in the House of Delegates as part of the 3rd district, 4th district, and 5th district.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p02] In the Virginia Senate, the city is represented as part of the 39th district.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p02] At the federal level, Alexandria is part of Virginia's 8th congressional district, represented by Democrat and Alexandria resident Don Beyer, elected in 2014.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p02] The state's senior member of the United States Senate is Democrat Mark Warner, first elected in 2008.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p02] The state's junior member of the United States Senate is Democrat Tim Kaine, first elected in 2012.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p02] Since its foundation, Alexandria's government has had several different forms of government.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p02] Before 1921, Alexandria had an elected eight-member Board of Aldermen and a sixteen-member Common Council whose members were elected by ward.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p02] In addition, there was an elected mayor with the power to veto legislation from the two councils.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p02] Reformers within the city during the early 20th century hoped to adopt the then-popular council-manager system.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p02] As a means to implementing this new system, the reformists proposed a plan to create a single city council elected at-large.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p02] This new system was adopted in 1921 and the first at-large councilmen were elected in June 1922.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p02] In 1930, Alexandria annexed the town of Potomac from Arlington County.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p02] Alexandria and Potomac stood in stark contrast.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p02] The streetcar suburb commuter town of Potomac had, as part of Arlington, been heavily influenced by the anti-vice crusades of staunch progressive Commonwealth's Attorney Crandal Mackey.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p02] In Potomac, slaughterhouses and saloons were banned.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p02] Residents of the former town of Potomac had a different identity from those in Alexandria, and after annexation former Potomac residents began to push for the reimplementation of the ward system.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p02] In a 1932 referendum, voters decided in favor of a new plan that would expand the city council to nine members; three elected at-large and six elected by ward.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p02] Support for the new plan was highest in the former town of Potomac.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p02] City councils elected under the new ward system began to take a more direct role in city administration.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p02] The city council and city manager gave conflicting orders to city employees while spending increased to accommodate appropriations coming from both the council and manager.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p02] With over one million dollars spent on unauthorized projects, a movement to go back to at-large councilmen emerged.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p02] In 1944, a referendum to eliminate the ward system ended with a vote in favor of the ward system.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p02] Shortly afterwards, a number of high-ranking city officials resigned, and residents appealed to the Circuit Court for an order to force a referendum.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p02] Unbeknownst to the city government, Delegate Armistead Boothe introduced a bill in Richmond to hold another referendum.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p02] This bill passed the General Assembly and a vote was held on March 2, 1948.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p02] The options in the referendum included retaining the extant system or replacing it with a council of seven at-large members.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p02] Voters approved the new system with 61% of votes in favor.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p02] More recently, a 1983 push by the Virginia NAACP to return to the ward system failed because of a lack of support from elected officials.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p02] In 2008 the City Council approved a charter where "citizens, businesses, and city government participate in a vibrant community that is always mindful of the needs and lifestyles of the generations to come".
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p02] That charter defined sustainability as "meeting our community's present needs while preserving our historic character and ensuring the ability of future generations to meet their own needs".
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p02] An ecocity is defined as "an ecologically healthy city".
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p02] In 2022, Alexandria enacted a 5-cent plastic bag tax consistent with the phase-out of lightweight plastic bags in the United States.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p02] Alexandria's primary law enforcement is the Alexandria Police Department (APD) which is led by a Chief of Police who is appointed by city government.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p02] In April 2022, Don Hayes was appointed as Chief of Police.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p02] As of 2023, the APD employs roughly 300 officers that receive training at the Northern Virginia Criminal Justice Training Academy.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p02] Every four years, Alexandria residents elect a sheriff that leads the Sheriff's Office in overseeing roughly 200 deputies and a detention center for pre-trial and short-term inmates.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p02] This jail is used to house pre-trial inmates in federal espionage cases.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p02] The Alexandria Fire Department is the city's fire protection and emergency medical services provider and is led by Fire/EMS Chief Corey A.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p02] The AFD operates 10 stations throughout the city and employs over 300 fire and EMS professionals.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p02] Virginia Tech's Washington-Alexandria Architecture Center, also known as WAAC, is located on Prince Street in Old Town, offering graduate programs in Urban Affairs and Planning, Public and International Affairs, Architecture, and Landscape Architecture.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p02] In 2018, Virginia Tech announced the construction of an "Innovation Campus" in Potomac Yard with graduate programs in computer science and computer engineering.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p02] Virginia Commonwealth University operates a Northern Virginia branch of its School of Social Work and The George Washington University also has a campus near the King Street–Old Town station.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p02] This campus mainly offers professional and vocational programs, such as an executive MBA program, urban planning and security studies.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p02] The city also has a campus of the Northern Virginia Community College.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p02] The largest seminary in the Episcopal Church, Virginia Theological Seminary, is located on Seminary Road.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p02] The city is served by the Alexandria City Public Schools system.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p02] Alexandria's public school system consists of twelve elementary schools for grades Kindergarten through 5th grade, with three of them also offering Pre-K.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p02] Two schools, Patrick Henry and Jefferson-Houston, are Pre-K through 8th grade schools while the middle schools, George Washington and Francis C.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p02] The demographics of the public school system contrast with those of the city.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p02] In 2008, only 14% of the students at Francis C.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p02] Hammond Middle School were non-Hispanic whites, compared to about 60% when looking at the city as a whole.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p02] 27% were of Hispanic descent, and 48% were black.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p02] About 9% of the school was of Asian descent.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p02] In 2004, 62% of school-going children received free lunches; by 2008, that number had decreased to 56%.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p02] At George Washington Middle School, 41% of students are non-Hispanic whites, 34% were Hispanic, 21% was black, and 2% of the students were Asian; 52% of students received free lunch.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p02] Alexandria City High School follows this trend as well; 23% of the students were classified as non-Hispanic whites, 25% as Hispanic, 44% as black, and 7% of the school was Asian; 47% of all students received free lunch.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p02] Alexandria is home to private schools such as St.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p02] Agnes School, Bishop Ireton High School, and Episcopal High School.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p02] Also in the city are Alexandria Country Day School, Commonwealth Academy, the Basilica School of Saint Mary, St.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p02] Rita's Catholic School, Blessed Sacrament School, and Global Health College.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p02] Alexandria is served by Inova Alexandria Hospital.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p02] The city's health department operates a health clinic at Mark Center in the city's West End and a teen wellness center at Alexandria City High School.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p02] Concurrent highways I-95 and I-495 (the Capital Beltway), including the Woodrow Wilson Bridge over the Potomac River, roughly parallels the city's southern boundary with Fairfax County before very briefly passing through D.C. and entering Maryland.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p02] I-395 crosses north and south through the western part of the city.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p02] Alexandria is bisected east and west by SR 7 (King Street).
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p02] The most western section of King Street in the city was once the terminus of the Leesburg Turnpike.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p02] SR 7 terminates at SR 400 (Washington Street), which connects the northern and southern segments of the George Washington Memorial Parkway.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p02] SR 236 (Duke Street) runs east–west along the southern side of the city, also terminating at VA 400 in Old Town.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p02] US 1 (Richmond Highway) passes north–south through the city, parallel and west of Washington Street and the George Washington Memorial Parkway.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p02] Through Old Town, the highway follows Patrick and Henry streets.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p02] The Alexandria city government operates its own mass transit system, the DASH bus, connecting points of interest with local transit hubs.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p02] DASH also offers a "trolley" diesel bus service on King Street from the King Street–Old Town Metro station to the Waterfront.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p02] Metrobus also serves Alexandria along with Metrorail's Blue and Yellow Lines with stops at Potomac Yard, Braddock Road, King Street-Old Town, Eisenhower Avenue, and Van Dorn Street.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p02] Hornblower Cruises operates the Potomac Water Taxi to and from Georgetown and The Wharf development in D.C. and the National Harbor development in Prince George's County.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p02] Union Station, the city's historic train station, has Amtrak intercity services and the Virginia Railway Express regional rail service.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p02] The station is directly adjacent to the King Street–Old Town Metro station.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p02] The traditional boundary between Old Town and the latterly annexed sections of the city follows the railway acquired by Virginia in 2021 and formerly owned by CSX Transportation.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p02] In addition, Norfolk Southern Railway operates a freight rail line and a transload terminal in the city.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p02] Capital Bikeshare, a bicycle-sharing public transportation system, launched in Alexandria in 2012.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p02] The system has 62 rental locations throughout the city.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p02] The East Coast Greenway and Mount Vernon Trail cycle routes pass through Alexandria.
[src:alexandria-virginia/alexandria-virginia-p02] Alexandria was twinned with Gyumri as a means of showing goodwill in the wake of the 1988 Armenian earthquake.
